## 4. Module Design

| ID | Module | Responsibility | Requirements |
|---|---|---|---|
| `DES-001` | API Transport Layer | Accepts requests, applies auth and validation, returns consistent responses | `FR-001`, `FR-002` |
| `DES-002` | Domain Service and Repository | Executes business rules and coordinates persistence and external dependencies | `FR-001` |

## 5. Data and State

- Core entities: request DTOs, domain entities, response DTOs, error objects
- Key fields: resource IDs, business state, version markers, request trace fields
- State transitions: receive request -> validate -> run business logic -> persist / call dependency -> return success or failure

## 6. Interfaces and Contracts

| Interface | Input | Output | Failure modes | Requirements |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `[HTTP] POST /v1/resources` | JSON body, auth credentials | resource ID, current state, trace fields | auth failure, invalid input, dependency timeout, write conflict | `FR-001`, `FR-002` |

## 7. Technical Decisions and Trade-Offs

- Decision: use explicit controller / service / repository layering and a shared error model
- Alternatives: put business logic and data access directly inside handlers
- Why not chosen: auth, validation, error handling, and testability all degrade quickly

Record important decisions in `docs/adr/` when appropriate.

